1
00:00:00,784 --> 00:00:02,771
Previously on "Manhattan"...

2
00:00:02,796 --> 00:00:07,499
Behold, gentlemen, 150 micrograms

3
00:00:07,524 --> 00:00:09,969
of plutonium-239.

4
00:00:10,003 --> 00:00:13,911
The sample is at Dr. Akley's disposal.

5
00:00:14,031 --> 00:00:16,171
I got keys to the lab. I can let you in.

6
00:00:16,327 --> 00:00:17,367
Really?

7
00:00:17,418 --> 00:00:19,786
What the hell is going on in here?

8
00:00:20,288 --> 00:00:23,623
You conned me into
giving you the plutonium.

9
00:00:23,625 --> 00:00:27,127
I got Frank Winter an outside line today.

10
00:00:27,178 --> 00:00:30,380
He said that you took
work from other scientists

11
00:00:30,431 --> 00:00:31,765
and published it as your own.

12
00:00:31,799 --> 00:00:33,434
That's bullshit, Abby.

13
00:00:33,466 --> 00:00:35,018
They're all whores?

14
00:00:35,808 --> 00:00:39,355
You whiz kids. Always in your heads.

15
00:00:39,390 --> 00:00:41,441
You deserve some fun every once in a while.

16
00:00:41,475 --> 00:00:43,393
As long as you're paid up...

17
00:00:49,100 --> 00:00:52,220
This chrysanthemum, it's
supposed to be white.

18
00:00:53,537 --> 00:00:56,156
My honey bees, they're dead.

19
00:00:56,158 --> 00:00:57,457
All of them.

20
00:02:26,413 --> 00:02:28,464
Guten Morgen, Dr. Heisenberg.

21
00:03:10,876 --> 00:03:13,076
Manhattan 1x06
Acceptable Limits

22
00:03:13,871 --> 00:03:18,184
Sync and corrections by Albanda
www.Addic7ed.com

23
00:03:21,018 --> 00:03:22,802
She's very well-read.
You should see the stack

24
00:03:22,804 --> 00:03:25,054
of books by her cot... Tolstoy, Voltaire.

25
00:03:25,105 --> 00:03:28,358
What progress have you made with
plutonium alloys for shaping?

26
00:03:28,392 --> 00:03:30,143
Aluminum reacts with the alpha particles,

27
00:03:30,145 --> 00:03:33,813
but gallium is a real possibility.

28
00:03:35,065 --> 00:03:38,902
But Jeannie's favorite is Charles Dickens.

29
00:03:38,953 --> 00:03:41,871
Now I think it's because she's an orphan.

30
00:03:41,906 --> 00:03:43,323
Isn't that sad?

31
00:03:43,374 --> 00:03:45,491
Did you find the melting point?

32
00:03:45,542 --> 00:03:47,410
Somewhere in the range of 900 kelvin.

33
00:03:47,461 --> 00:03:50,496
How did you know that Mrs.
Winter was the girl for you?

34
00:03:50,498 --> 00:03:54,384
Was it a eureka like Einstein
discovering special relativity?

35
00:03:54,418 --> 00:03:55,969
That took Albert a couple of years.

36
00:03:55,994 --> 00:03:59,345
- Okay, but with Jeannie...
- Look, if we want more plutonium,

37
00:03:59,473 --> 00:04:02,759
we have to prove that we know what we're
doing with this miniscule amount we have.

38
00:04:02,810 --> 00:04:05,228
X-10 Reactor goes critical this week.

39
00:04:05,262 --> 00:04:07,764
By Christmas, they're gonna
be pumping out plutonium.

40
00:04:07,815 --> 00:04:09,983
So I don't need possibilities, Fritz.

41
00:04:10,017 --> 00:04:11,966
I don't need ranges.

42
00:04:12,520 --> 00:04:14,354
I need real data.

43
00:04:28,752 --> 00:04:31,454
Thought we only got poked
and prodded once a month.

44
00:04:33,874 --> 00:04:36,709
See more of you than I
do my wife these days.

45
00:04:41,048 --> 00:04:43,599
Something wrong with my
last urine collection?

46
00:04:45,436 --> 00:04:47,890
Fit as a bull moose, Mr. Isaacs.

47
00:04:48,897 --> 00:04:52,166
Just establishing your
baseline before your big trip.

48
00:04:53,594 --> 00:04:54,945
What trip?

49
00:05:00,117 --> 00:05:02,068
We're not shipping you off to Guadalcanal.

50
00:05:02,119 --> 00:05:03,536
This is a good thing.

51
00:05:03,570 --> 00:05:05,238
Gerald, give us a moment.

52
00:05:17,051 --> 00:05:18,584
Forgive the cloak and dagger,

53
00:05:18,586 --> 00:05:21,838
but the army can't have
functioning nuclear reactor

54
00:05:21,889 --> 00:05:23,506
on its travel bulletin.

55
00:05:24,758 --> 00:05:26,559
The reactor's gone critical.

56
00:05:26,593 --> 00:05:30,205
We're about to have our very own plutonium
factory. If our colleagues don't wipe

57
00:05:30,230 --> 00:05:32,216
the Confederate states
off the face of the Earth.

58
00:05:32,241 --> 00:05:34,761
You leave for Tennessee tomorrow morning.

59
00:05:35,270 --> 00:05:37,140
Tomorrow morning?

60
00:05:37,165 --> 00:05:38,699
It's just...

61
00:05:40,227 --> 00:05:42,020
- Um...
- What?

62
00:05:42,045 --> 00:05:43,545
I've never flown in a plane before.

63
00:05:44,853 --> 00:05:45,945
And...

64
00:05:47,781 --> 00:05:49,916
honestly,

65
00:05:49,950 --> 00:05:53,286
I get queasy when I'm too
high up at Fenway Park.

66
00:05:56,673 --> 00:05:58,153
Charlie,

67
00:06:00,044 --> 00:06:03,513
for weeks you're been sitting at your desk

68
00:06:03,547 --> 00:06:06,966
hoping I wouldn't notice you eyeing
the clock like a high school senior.

69
00:06:07,017 --> 00:06:09,936
Look, I know you have certain
reservations about the project.

70
00:06:10,506 --> 00:06:12,305
But in less than 72 hours,

71
00:06:12,356 --> 00:06:15,638
the world's second nuclear
reactor is going to go hot.

72
00:06:16,144 --> 00:06:18,728
Now, you want to sit in the
nosebleed seats of history?

73
00:06:19,797 --> 00:06:22,021
Or do you want to sit in the dugout?

74
00:06:22,866 --> 00:06:24,951
So it's our second anniversary

75
00:06:24,985 --> 00:06:29,055
and there is Frank cradling
this unwrapped brown box

76
00:06:29,089 --> 00:06:30,706
like it is the Ark of the Covenant.

77
00:06:30,741 --> 00:06:32,792
He never remembers our anniversary.

78
00:06:32,826 --> 00:06:35,878
And inside the box is a rabbit.

79
00:06:35,913 --> 00:06:39,999
Now, Frank tells me it is
a symbol of our marriage.

80
00:06:40,033 --> 00:06:42,835
Something about a spirit of curiosity

81
00:06:42,870 --> 00:06:44,437
and a keen mating instinct.

82
00:06:44,471 --> 00:06:45,671
Okay.

83
00:06:45,673 --> 00:06:47,840
Anyway, a week later, this rabbit

84
00:06:47,842 --> 00:06:49,759
is covered in sores

85
00:06:49,810 --> 00:06:52,011
and it's banging its head
against the side of the cage.

86
00:06:52,062 --> 00:06:54,299
And the next thing I
know, the rabbit is dead.

87
00:06:54,324 --> 00:06:56,649
Well, I hope you gave the
breeder a piece of your mind.

88
00:06:56,683 --> 00:06:58,234
Breeder?

89
00:06:58,268 --> 00:07:02,021
Frank stole the rabbit from
the natural sciences lab.

90
00:07:02,072 --> 00:07:04,073
But he failed to notice the poor creature

91
00:07:04,108 --> 00:07:06,325
was an infectious diseases study.

92
00:07:07,297 --> 00:07:09,028
Treponema cuniculi.

93
00:07:09,079 --> 00:07:11,551
Oh, you gave your wife
syphilis. That's nice.

94
00:07:11,576 --> 00:07:13,583
Never was very good at biology.

95
00:07:13,617 --> 00:07:17,058
He has other qualities to redeem him.

96
00:07:17,245 --> 00:07:18,704
The only cook in the house.

97
00:07:18,755 --> 00:07:20,756
Beef Bourguignon.

98
00:07:20,791 --> 00:07:23,042
Salt recklessly.

99
00:07:23,710 --> 00:07:25,105
Oh.

100
00:07:25,796 --> 00:07:28,681
Well, isn't this romantic?

101
00:07:31,101 --> 00:07:33,052
Oh, Helen.

102
00:07:50,320 --> 00:07:52,321
- You're done?
- Yeah.

103
00:07:52,372 --> 00:07:54,790
Oh.

104
00:07:54,825 --> 00:07:58,077
Oh, God.

105
00:07:58,079 --> 00:07:59,662
- Okay.
- Oh, God.

106
00:07:59,713 --> 00:08:02,081
What's this?

107
00:08:07,760 --> 00:08:09,711
They're playing
"Casablanca" at the theater.

108
00:08:11,475 --> 00:08:15,344
Or we could just talk.

109
00:08:17,147 --> 00:08:19,232
What do you want to talk about?

110
00:08:19,266 --> 00:08:21,317
Um...

111
00:08:21,351 --> 00:08:25,238
Did you do good science today?

112
00:08:28,609 --> 00:08:30,526
You know what, Corporal?

113
00:08:30,577 --> 00:08:32,695
I have an early morning.

114
00:08:33,990 --> 00:08:36,115
Why don't you take me home?

115
00:08:36,117 --> 00:08:40,419
Or, no, drop me off at the PX.

116
00:08:44,291 --> 00:08:47,376
You haven't told anyone
about this, have you?

117
00:08:47,427 --> 00:08:49,378
That I'm dating a genius?

118
00:08:49,673 --> 00:08:51,547
We're not dating.

119
00:08:56,503 --> 00:08:57,670
Abby.

120
00:09:03,393 --> 00:09:05,144
- Hey.
- Hello.

121
00:09:05,698 --> 00:09:07,396
What are you doing?

122
00:09:08,051 --> 00:09:09,899
I lied.

123
00:09:11,105 --> 00:09:12,735
I told you I read your paper.

124
00:09:12,786 --> 00:09:14,687
I picked it up about 10 times last year,

125
00:09:14,721 --> 00:09:17,490
but I never got past the first paragraph.

126
00:09:17,524 --> 00:09:19,458
Now I want to finish.

127
00:09:20,612 --> 00:09:21,794
Why?

128
00:09:22,174 --> 00:09:24,664
This part about bending light waves,

129
00:09:24,666 --> 00:09:27,166
is that like a prism? We had one at school.

130
00:09:27,217 --> 00:09:28,751
- Abby.
- Hmm?

131
00:09:29,391 --> 00:09:31,053
Put it away.

132
00:09:32,839 --> 00:09:34,757
What?

133
00:09:35,638 --> 00:09:37,510
You ever gonna let it go?

134
00:09:38,255 --> 00:09:40,322
I just wanted to read it.

135
00:09:41,354 --> 00:09:43,266
This is about Frank Winter.

136
00:09:45,152 --> 00:09:46,435
Ever since you got that call,

137
00:09:46,486 --> 00:09:47,737
you haven't looked at me the same.

138
00:09:47,771 --> 00:09:49,355
That's ridiculous.

139
00:09:49,406 --> 00:09:51,440
I didn't go to Milton
Academy like your father.

140
00:09:51,491 --> 00:09:52,992
I don't have a trust fund.

141
00:09:53,026 --> 00:09:55,361
Guess that means I
cheated my way in, right?

142
00:09:55,412 --> 00:09:57,747
You are the only person I know

143
00:09:57,781 --> 00:10:00,366
who thinks a decent upbringing
is something to be ashamed of.

144
00:10:03,870 --> 00:10:05,705
Where's my suitcase?

145
00:10:05,707 --> 00:10:06,988
Why?

146
00:10:07,207 --> 00:10:09,138
I have to go on a trip tomorrow.

147
00:10:09,753 --> 00:10:11,961
I don't know when I'll be back.

148
00:10:12,129 --> 00:10:14,430
You'll have lots of time
to catch up on your reading.

149
00:10:16,850 --> 00:10:19,051
I am going to prove that
it was army pesticides

150
00:10:19,053 --> 00:10:20,720
and then I'm going to take
it to the town council.

151
00:10:20,722 --> 00:10:23,055
The combined IQ of the town council

152
00:10:23,106 --> 00:10:24,995
is probably half of yours.

153
00:10:25,020 --> 00:10:27,373
Come to the meeting with
me Saturday, won't you?

154
00:10:27,477 --> 00:10:29,612
Frank refuses.

155
00:10:29,646 --> 00:10:32,648
Well, if you two are done conspiring,
I think we should get back.

156
00:10:32,699 --> 00:10:35,067
But there is one more
little thing before you go.

157
00:10:37,120 --> 00:10:39,405
You know, the Nazis say they cause cancer.

158
00:10:39,407 --> 00:10:41,707
Actually, it's a little bigger than this.

159
00:10:41,742 --> 00:10:43,909
I need a contrast microscope

160
00:10:43,960 --> 00:10:46,078
if I'm gonna shore up
my case against the army.

161
00:10:46,080 --> 00:10:48,447
Do you think you could smuggle
one out of the lab for me?

162
00:10:48,482 --> 00:10:50,716
I wish we could.

163
00:10:50,751 --> 00:10:52,918
Roosevelt couldn't get his wheelchair

164
00:10:52,920 --> 00:10:55,254
out of the tech area
without the army's say-so.

165
00:10:56,840 --> 00:10:58,090
Thank you, my dear.

166
00:10:58,092 --> 00:10:59,842
- Good night.
- Good night.

167
00:11:24,117 --> 00:11:26,252
Uh...

168
00:11:46,523 --> 00:11:51,143
Make clear all areas on
designation six through nine.

169
00:11:51,145 --> 00:11:53,145
Make clear all areas...

170
00:11:53,987 --> 00:11:55,614
Jeannie.

171
00:11:55,649 --> 00:11:58,284
I waited all night for you to knock.

172
00:11:58,318 --> 00:12:01,237
Oh, I'm so sorry. I've
been chained to my desk.

173
00:12:01,288 --> 00:12:04,457
But I have been driving the
warden crazy talking about you.

174
00:12:06,159 --> 00:12:08,327
I cut it into triangles the way you like

175
00:12:08,378 --> 00:12:10,663
in case you don't make it to breakfast.

176
00:12:15,502 --> 00:12:17,420
You made me a PB&J?

177
00:12:21,228 --> 00:12:22,729
It's $2.50.

178
00:12:23,844 --> 00:12:25,311
For the sandwich?

179
00:12:25,345 --> 00:12:27,096
For last night.

180
00:12:27,147 --> 00:12:30,816
I'm sorry. I have a
24-hours cancellation policy.

181
00:12:30,851 --> 00:12:32,685
Sure, sure.

182
00:12:41,995 --> 00:12:43,696
Bye.

183
00:12:43,698 --> 00:12:45,348
Bye.

184
00:14:23,213 --> 00:14:25,431
Oh! What the...

185
00:14:25,465 --> 00:14:29,051
No, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no.

186
00:14:35,185 --> 00:14:37,114
You'll be traveling under an assumed name.

187
00:14:37,139 --> 00:14:38,162
Yes, sir.

188
00:14:38,196 --> 00:14:40,748
The workers at Site X barely know
what they're making down there

189
00:14:40,799 --> 00:14:42,082
much less what it's used for.

190
00:14:42,133 --> 00:14:44,001
Let's take a look under the hood

191
00:14:44,026 --> 00:14:46,728
and make sure we're not
blowing a 20-kiloton gasket.

192
00:14:48,109 --> 00:14:50,861
They must have a team of experts
making sure that won't happen.

193
00:14:50,912 --> 00:14:53,113
Let's just say the army is
more concerned with secrecy

194
00:14:53,164 --> 00:14:55,332
than they are with something
as trivial as public safety.

195
00:14:55,367 --> 00:14:57,618
Nothing goes forward without
your say-so down there, Charlie.

196
00:14:59,087 --> 00:15:01,449
I thought you said I was
the only man for the job.

197
00:15:03,488 --> 00:15:05,125
You are.

198
00:15:06,878 --> 00:15:08,679
Occasionally we have to
throw implosion a bone

199
00:15:08,713 --> 00:15:11,348
to keep them from chewing
through their leashes.

200
00:15:11,383 --> 00:15:12,850
- Sir.
- Have a good trip.

201
00:15:12,884 --> 00:15:14,476
Thank you.

202
00:15:15,431 --> 00:15:18,284
Be careful at the airport.

203
00:15:18,640 --> 00:15:20,898
You know, there are thieves everywhere.

204
00:15:21,810 --> 00:15:24,895
Charlie, you want to get these?

205
00:15:33,386 --> 00:15:35,539
My father was knighted by King George

206
00:15:35,573 --> 00:15:37,958
and yet Frank sends a
little Dutch girl to Site X.

207
00:15:37,993 --> 00:15:40,527
Well, Helen's got more
degrees than a thermometer.

208
00:15:40,562 --> 00:15:42,579
You are just jealous.

209
00:15:42,631 --> 00:15:45,165
Close the door. We could
lose it in the wind.

210
00:15:46,751 --> 00:15:48,836
Looks like you've already lost it, Louis.

211
00:15:48,870 --> 00:15:50,738
I was reducing the metal and there was...

212
00:15:50,772 --> 00:15:53,741
an unexpected reaction.
We're missing 24 micrograms.

213
00:15:53,775 --> 00:15:55,476
Of plutonium?

214
00:15:55,510 --> 00:15:58,178
You've misplaced a million
dollars' worth of Pu-239?

215
00:15:58,229 --> 00:16:01,065
The Snoop's going haywire,
but I swiped the floor clean

216
00:16:01,099 --> 00:16:03,368
and the oil paper's good.

217
00:16:04,853 --> 00:16:07,604
We'll find it. Plutonium
doesn't just evaporate.

218
00:16:07,656 --> 00:16:10,107
Our careers will when
Oppenheimer gets wind of this.

219
00:16:10,158 --> 00:16:12,026
Okay.

220
00:16:29,127 --> 00:16:31,178
Mine's not making a sound.

221
00:16:31,212 --> 00:16:33,380
Nope, nor mine.

222
00:16:33,431 --> 00:16:36,633
This one must be busted.

223
00:16:36,685 --> 00:16:39,219
It beeps everywhere I look, but
nothing shows up under the scope.

224
00:16:39,270 --> 00:16:41,271
- Here, let me see it.
- Yeah.

225
00:17:01,960 --> 00:17:04,328
We need a medic.

226
00:17:07,582 --> 00:17:09,299
You moving to Tennessee?

227
00:17:10,668 --> 00:17:12,636
I packed less when I left for Harvard.

228
00:17:12,670 --> 00:17:15,055
That word rolls so easy off your tongue.

229
00:17:15,090 --> 00:17:16,840
"Can you pass the sugar?
I went to Harvard."

230
00:17:16,891 --> 00:17:18,759
How many pairs of clogs do you need?

231
00:17:18,810 --> 00:17:21,478
By the way, I found a problem
with your little space paper.

232
00:17:22,315 --> 00:17:24,515
The word is affect, not effect.

233
00:17:24,566 --> 00:17:26,600
A typo on page six.

234
00:17:26,602 --> 00:17:28,102
Embarrassing.

235
00:17:28,104 --> 00:17:29,319
Hello.

236
00:17:29,354 --> 00:17:31,271
Tickets, please.

237
00:17:31,322 --> 00:17:32,495
Yeah.

238
00:17:39,147 --> 00:17:41,365
Mr. and Mrs. Donaldson.

239
00:17:41,838 --> 00:17:43,288
That's us.

240
00:17:43,313 --> 00:17:44,952
Right, honey pie?

241
00:17:45,003 --> 00:17:48,255
Must be quite the big shot to fly
your wife to the Smoky Mountains.

242
00:17:48,289 --> 00:17:50,758
Oh, actually, I've been supporting Billy

243
00:17:50,792 --> 00:17:52,626
since his hunting accident.

244
00:17:52,628 --> 00:17:55,295
It doesn't matter to me that
he can't hold down a job...

245
00:17:55,346 --> 00:17:57,181
or have children.

246
00:17:57,215 --> 00:17:59,299
Oh.

